Consider the matrices in Activity. First we set up the . Again, we use the proper zero vector on the right-hand side, and then we combine the expression on the left-hand side into one vector so that we may compare against the zero vector.
k_1\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} + k_2\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1\\1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix} + k_3\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}k_1 \amp 0\\0 \amp k_1\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp k_2\\k_2 \amp 0\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\0 \amp k_3\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}k_1 \amp k_2\\k_2 \amp k_1+k_3\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}
There is no need to set up a system of equations here we can see from comparing the top rows on either side that k_1=0 and k_2=0. Then, from the (2,2) entries, we see that k_1+k_3=0. But since we already have k_1=0, we get k_3=0 as well. So there is only the trivial solution, and these vectors are linearly independent.
